702859f-a.title: Brooklyn: 84th Street - 16th Avenue
702859f-a.text:
(1)
84th Street, north side, east of Sixteenth Ave., showing J. Lott
Nostrand house, built about 1670. During the Revolution it bacame
the William Barrie Tavern, at which George Washington is said to have
stopped in 1790. Judge John Lott Nostrand was born here in 1856 and
lived here until 1902. It was demolished in 1914, to make way for
the widening of 84th Street.
About 1900.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
MAY BE REPPODUCED.
(2)
The same, showing the N.E. corner after the demolition of the
house.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
MAY BE REPRODUCED.

702861f-b.title: Brooklyn: 84th Street - 16th Avenue
702861f-b.text:
(1)
84th Street, east of Sixteenth Ave; showing St. Johns German Evan-
gelical Church.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
MAY BE REPRODUCED.
(2)
The same; showing a memorial marker in the cemetery near the Church.
This commemorates the house in which General Woodhull died in 1775.
The house was erected in 1657, Rutgert Joosten Van Brunt purchased it in
1674. It was demolished in 1836, the last occupant, Barent Wyckoff,
having inherited it from Rutgert 3. Van Brunt. A Photograph of adraw-
ing has been sent to Room 308, the Print Room.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
MAY BE REPRODUCED.
